under luteinising hormone control","Peritubular cells under testosterone control"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESertoli cells under follicle stimulating hormone control\u003C/strong\u003E is correct. Androgen binding protein is synthesised and secreted by Sertoli cells in response to follicle stimulating hormone. This protein binds testosterone with high affinity, maintaining elevated concentrations within the seminiferous tubules which is essential for normal spermatogenesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeydig cells under luteinising hormone control\u003C/strong\u003E - While Leydig cells produce testosterone in response to luteinising hormone, they do not produce androgen binding protein\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeritubular cells under testosterone control\u003C/strong\u003E - Peritubular cells provide structural support to seminiferous tubules but do not produce androgen binding protein\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpermatogonia under inhibin control\u003C/strong\u003E - Spermatogonia are developing sperm cells and do not produce regulatory proteins\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpididymal cells under oestradiol control\u003C/strong\u003E - Epididymal cells are involved in sperm maturation but do not produce androgen binding protein\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe high local testosterone concentration maintained by androgen binding protein supports sperm cell development and maturation within the seminiferous tubules.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Androgen binding protein is produced by Sertoli cells in response to follicle stimulating hormone stimulation.","The primary function of androgen binding protein is to concentrate testosterone within the seminiferous tubules.","High local testosterone concentrations are essential for normal spermatogenesis."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61575"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18600"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61575","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61575"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T23:53:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T23:54:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11332"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76074"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4934"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Reproductive System (